00:01:11.599 --> 00:01:18.639
One of the most common questions we're asked about Positron is, when should I pay for Positron?

00:01:18.639 --> 00:01:24.639
Just like with RStudio, we distribute two versions of Positron, a free, source-available

00:01:24.639 --> 00:01:30.760
desktop application for Mac, Windows, or Linux that's called Positron Desktop, or

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:38.760
more often, just Positron, and Positron Pro, a commercially licensed, native server version

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:48.239
of Positron that's accessible via browser and only available in Posit Workbench.

00:01:48.239 --> 00:01:51.879
What are the key differences in features and capabilities between Positron and Positron

00:01:51.879 --> 00:01:52.879
Pro?

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:57.839
Well, I've tried to list everything worth mentioning here, but the key message is that

00:01:57.839 --> 00:02:03.480
our goal is and has always been that the Positron development experience you know and love is

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:08.279
fully available in the free desktop application.

00:02:08.279 --> 00:02:12.800
Unlike other IDEs, we don't want you to have to pay for a Pro version of our software to

00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:18.339
unlock a better development experience that's tailored for data science.

00:02:18.339 --> 00:02:25.020
In the free desktop version of Positron, you can code natively in both R and Python,

00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:30.660
install OpenVSX-compatible extensions, customize your layout with dedicated panes for data

00:02:30.660 --> 00:02:37.419
science work, push and pull code from version control, preview data apps, and even publish

00:02:37.419 --> 00:02:45.580
Deposit Connect and use Positron's AI capabilities without needing a Positron Pro license.

00:02:45.580 --> 00:02:49.860
With Positron Pro, you get the same data science development experience you know and

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:53.259
love from the free version of Positron.

00:02:53.259 --> 00:02:57.940
You also get to benefit from the capabilities built into Posit Workbench, our professional

00:02:57.940 --> 00:03:05.580
data science workbench that includes Positron, RStudio, VS Code, and JupyterLab.

00:03:05.580 --> 00:03:11.979
Things like single sign-on, managed credentials for accessing enterprise data in AWS, Snowflake,

00:03:11.979 --> 00:03:18.699
or Databricks, scalable and customizable compute, monitoring and auditing tools for

00:03:18.699 --> 00:03:28.740
IT and compliance, and dedicated support from Posit engineers when something goes wrong.

00:03:28.740 --> 00:03:32.860
To put it another way, when should you pay for Positron?

00:03:32.860 --> 00:03:39.639
Well, when you need to take Positron to work.

00:03:39.639 --> 00:03:44.839
When you have several colleagues who also use Positron, or who prefer RStudio, VS Code,

00:03:44.839 --> 00:03:48.440
or JupyterLab for their development work.

00:03:48.440 --> 00:03:52.779
When IT has concerns about the security and management of local desktop installations

00:03:52.779 --> 00:03:57.320
of data science software, or when they want greater monitoring and auditability of your

00:03:57.320 --> 00:04:00.320
use of that software.

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:03.759
When you and your colleagues are working with datasets that are larger than your laptop

00:04:03.759 --> 00:04:08.919
